	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(center)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> <date>August 28th 5610</date></p>
				<p>To Messrs <addressee>C Lichten</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><addressee>E Bamberger</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><addressee>L. Silberman</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(2)"><placeName>Louisville</placeName>.</p>
				<p>Gentlemen</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Yours of <date>August 15</date> postmarked the <date>23</date> came to hand this mor&#45;<lb/>ning&#44; and it appears at first sight singular that 8 days should have<lb/> passed between it being written and marked&#8212;for the second place<lb/> I have no personal knowledge whatsoever of the <persName>Rev. H. C. Henry</persName><lb/> never having met him in my life&#44; and not having examined any<lb/> of his writings or credentials. But <persName>Rev. Dr. Raphall</persName> of the <placeName>Elm<lb/> Street</placeName> Synagogue <placeName>New York</placeName> has some personal knowledge of<lb/> him&#44; as also my friend <persName>Rev. J. K. Gutheim</persName> late of <placeName>Cincinnati</placeName><lb/> whose place <persName>Mr. <add>&#63;</add></persName> obtained last <add>&#63;</add>. I have no<lb/> doubt that if your election is postponed for two or three months<lb/> <add>&#63;</add> could correspond with these two ministers &#38; <persName>Mr.<lb/> Henry&#39;s</persName> late congregation in <placeName>London</placeName>&#44; you will obtain all<lb/> the information necessary and which <persName>Mr H</persName> will I presume be glad<lb/> to furnish.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">At the same time I hope that I do not trespass so far<lb/> on your patience gentlemen for saying that I trust that no<lb/> intention is entertained of setting aside the <persName>Rev. Mr Gotthelf</persName><lb/> in favor of a new comer&#44; unless there exist some urgent reasons for<lb/> his dismissal of which I have not heard. As respects <persName>Mr<lb/> Henry</persName> I confess that I am not favorably impressed of him&#44;<lb/> owing to his being instrumental in <persName>Mr Gutheim</persName> being deprived<lb/> of his office&#44; though he has some better one than he had before&#59;<lb/> and that <persName>Mr Henry</persName> had no right to refer to me at all&#44; as we exchan&#45;<lb/>ged but one letter&#44; and never had any intercourse whatever before his<lb/> quitting <placeName>Europe</placeName> and since his arrival here. Of course I have<lb/> no personal ill&#45;will to him&#59; but I do not approve of any one trying</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>to obtain the situation of another especially when he has a position which<lb/> secures him a living. But as you do not ask my opinion to govern you<lb/> in your choice&#44; I have to repeat that I <del>&#63;</del> refer you to those<lb/> having the information desired to enable you to come to a correct<lb/> judgment.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">It is my sincere hope that you may resolve<lb/> on the best method to promote the interest of our Religion&#44; and<lb/> that peace &#38;  good will may reside among you. I need not add<lb/> that I shall be happy to be of any service in my power to your<lb/> congregation &#38;  you individually for the kind consideration manifested<lb/> towards me and my public labours.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Wishing you <add>Hebrew</add> and that your prayers may<lb/> be answered.</p>
			<p rend="indent(9)">I am</p>
			<p rend="indent(9)">Resp your obt servt</p>
			<p rend="indent(10)"><persName role="author">Isaac Leeser</persName></p>
		</body>
